# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: satellite-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:satellite-networking/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A **communications satellite** is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for television, telephone, radio, internet, and military applications.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] However, most form satellite constellations in low Earth orbit, where ground antennas must track the satellites and switch between them frequently.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The radio waves used for telecommunications links travel by line of sight and so are obstructed by the curve of the Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The purpose of communications satellites is to relay the signal around the curve of the Earth allowing communication between widely separated geographical points.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites operate across a wide range of radio and microwave frequencies.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] To avoid signal interference, international organizations have regulations for which frequency ranges or "bands" certain organizations are allowed to use.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This allocation of bands minimizes the risk of signal interference.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Clarke published an article titled "Extraterrestrial Relays" in the British magazine *Wireless World*.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The article described the fundamentals behind the deployment of artificial satellites in geostationary orbits to relay radio signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Clarke is often quoted as being the inventor of the concept of the communications satellite, and the term 'Clarke Belt' is employed as a description of the orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The first artificial Earth satellite was Sputnik 1, which was put into orbit by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It was developed by Mikhail Tikhonravov and Sergey Korolev, building on work by Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Sputnik 1 was equipped with an on-board radio transmitter that worked on two frequencies of 20.005 and 40.002 MHz, or 7 and 15 meters wavelength.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The satellite was not placed in orbit to send data from one point on Earth to another, but the radio transmitter was meant to study the properties of radio wave distribution throughout the ionosphere.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The launch of Sputnik 1 was a major step in the exploration of space and rocket development, and marks the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] There are two major classes of communications satellites, *passive* and *active*.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Passive satellites only reflect the signal coming from the source, toward the direction of the receiver.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] With passive satellites, the reflected signal is not amplified at the satellite, and only a small amount of the transmitted energy actually reaches the receiver.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Since the satellite is so far above Earth, the radio signal is attenuated due to free-space path loss, so the signal received on Earth is very weak.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Active satellites, on the other hand, amplify the received signal before retransmitting it to the receiver on the ground.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Passive satellites were the first communications satellites, but are little used now.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Work that was begun in the field of electrical intelligence gathering at the United States Naval Research Laboratory in 1951 led to a project named Communication Moon Relay.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] After achieving the first transoceanic communication between Washington, D.C., and Hawaii on 23 January 1956, this system was publicly inaugurated and put into formal production in January 1960.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The first satellite purpose-built to actively relay communications was Project SCORE, led by Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) and launched on 18 December 1958, which used a tape recorder to carry a stored voice message, as well as to receive, store, and retransmit messages.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It was used to send a Christmas greeting to the world from U.S.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The satellite also executed several realtime transmissions before the non-rechargeable batteries failed on 30 December 1958 after eight hours of actual operation.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The direct successor to SCORE was another ARPA-led project called Courier.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Courier 1B was launched on 4 October 1960 to explore whether it would be possible to establish a global military communications network by using "delayed repeater" satellites, which receive and store information until commanded to rebroadcast them.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] After 17 days, a command system failure ended communications from the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] NASA's satellite applications program launched the first artificial satellite used for passive relay communications in Echo 1 on 12 August 1960.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Echo 1 was an aluminized balloon satellite acting as a passive reflector of microwave signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Communication signals were bounced off the satellite from one point on Earth to another.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This experiment sought to establish the feasibility of worldwide broadcasts of telephone, radio, and television signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Telstar was the first active, direct relay communications commercial satellite and marked the first transatlantic transmission of television signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Another passive relay experiment primarily intended for military communications purposes was Project West Ford, which was led by Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] After an initial failure in 1961, a launch on 9 May 1963 dispersed 350 million copper needle dipoles to create a passive reflecting belt.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Even though only about half of the dipoles properly separated from each other, the project was able to successfully experiment and communicate using frequencies in the SHF X band spectrum.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] An immediate antecedent of the geostationary satellites was the Hughes Aircraft Company's Syncom 2, launched on 26 July 1963.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Syncom 2 was the first communications satellite in a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It revolved around the Earth once per day at constant speed, but because it still had north–south motion, special equipment was needed to track it.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Its successor, Syncom 3, launched on 19 July 1964, was the first geostationary communications satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Syncom 3 obtained a geosynchronous orbit, without a north–south motion, making it appear from the ground as a stationary object in the sky.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A direct extension of the passive experiments of Project West Ford was the Lincoln Experimental Satellite program, also conducted by the Lincoln Laboratory on behalf of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The LES-1 active communications satellite was launched on 11 February 1965 to explore the feasibility of active solid-state X band long-range military communications.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A total of nine satellites were launched between 1965 and 1976 as part of this series.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In the United States, 1962 saw the creation of the Communications Satellite Corporation (COMSAT) private corporation, which was subject to instruction by the US Government on matters of national policy.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Over the next two years, international negotiations led to the Intelsat Agreements, which in turn led to the launch of Intelsat 1, also known as Early Bird, on 6 April 1965, and which was the first commercial communications satellite to be placed in geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Subsequent Intelsat launches in the 1960s provided multi-destination service and video, audio, and data service to ships at sea (Intelsat 2 in 1966–67), and the completion of a fully global network with Intelsat 3 in 1969–70.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] When Intelsat was launched, the United States was the only launch source outside of the Soviet Union, who did not participate in the Intelsat agreements.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Soviet Union launched its first communications satellite on 23 April 1965 as part of the Molniya program.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This program was also unique at the time for its use of what then became known as the Molniya orbit, which describes a highly elliptical orbit, with two high apogees daily over the northern hemisphere.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This orbit provides a long dwell time over Russian territory as well as over Canada at higher latitudes than geostationary orbits over the equator.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In the 2020s, the popularity of low Earth orbit satellite internet constellations providing relatively low-cost internet services led to reducing demand for new geostationary orbit communications satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites usually have one of three primary types of orbit, while other orbital classifications are used to further specify orbital details.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] MEO and LEO are non-geostationary orbit (NGSO).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] As satellites in MEO and LEO orbit the Earth faster, they do not remain visible in the sky to a fixed point on Earth continually like a geostationary satellite, but appear to a ground observer to cross the sky and "set" when they go behind the Earth beyond the visible horizon.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Therefore, to provide continuous communications capability with these lower orbits requires a larger number of satellites, so that one of these satellites will always be visible in the sky for transmission of communication signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] However, due to their closer distance to the Earth, LEO or MEO satellites can communicate to ground with reduced latency and at lower power than would be required from a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A low Earth orbit (LEO) typically is a circular orbit about 160 to 2,000 kilometres (99 to 1,243 mi) above the Earth's surface and, correspondingly, a period (time to revolve around the Earth) of about 90 minutes.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Because of their low altitude, these satellites are only visible from within a radius of roughly 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) from the sub-satellite point.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In addition, satellites in low Earth orbit change their position relative to the ground position quickly.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] So even for local applications, many satellites are needed if the mission requires uninterrupted connectivity.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Low-Earth-orbiting satellites are less expensive to launch into orbit than geostationary satellites and, due to proximity to the ground, do not require as high signal strength (signal strength falls off as the square of the distance from the source, so the effect is considerable).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Thus there is a trade off between the number of satellites and their cost.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In addition, there are important differences in the onboard and ground equipment needed to support the two types of missions.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A group of satellites working in concert is known as a satellite constellation.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Two such constellations, intended to provide satellite phone and low-speed data services, primarily to remote areas, are the Iridium and Globalstar systems.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Iridium system has 66 satellites, which orbital inclination of 86.4° and inter-satellite links provide service availability over the entire surface of Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Starlink is a satellite internet constellation operated by SpaceX, that aims for global satellite Internet access coverage.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It is also possible to offer discontinuous coverage using a low-Earth-orbit satellite capable of storing data received while passing over one part of Earth and transmitting it later while passing over another part.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This will be the case with the CASCADE system of Canada's CASSIOPE communications satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Another system using this store and forward method is Orbcomm.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A medium Earth orbit is a satellite in orbit somewhere between 2,000 and 35,786 kilometres (1,243 and 22,236 mi) above the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are similar to LEO satellites in functionality.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are visible for much longer periods of time than LEO satellites, usually between 2 and 8 hours.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] MEO satellites have a larger coverage area than LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A MEO satellite's longer duration of visibility and wider footprint means fewer satellites are needed in a MEO network than a LEO network.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] One disadvantage is that a MEO satellite's distance gives it a longer time delay and weaker signal than a LEO satellite, although these limitations are not as severe as those of a GEO satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Like LEOs, these satellites do not maintain a stationary distance from the Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This is in contrast to the geostationary orbit, where satellites are always 35,786 kilometres (22,236 mi) from Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Typically the orbit of a medium Earth orbit satellite is about 16,000 kilometres (10,000 mi) above Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In various patterns, these satellites make the trip around Earth in anywhere from 2 to 8 hours.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] To an observer on Earth, a satellite in a geostationary orbit appears motionless, in a fixed position in the sky.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This is because it revolves around the Earth at Earth's own angular velocity (one revolution per sidereal day, in an equatorial orbit).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A geostationary orbit is useful for communications because ground antennas can be aimed at the satellite without their having to track the satellite's motion.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In applications that require many ground antennas, such as DirecTV distribution, the savings in ground equipment can more than outweigh the cost and complexity of placing a satellite into orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] By 2000, Hughes Space and Communications (now Boeing Satellite Development Center) had built nearly 40 percent of the more than one hundred satellites in service worldwide.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Geostationary satellites must operate above the equator and therefore appear lower on the horizon as the receiver gets farther from the equator.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This will cause problems for extreme northerly latitudes, affecting connectivity and causing multipath interference (caused by signals reflecting off the ground and into the ground antenna).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Thus, for areas close to the North (and South) Pole, a geostationary satellite may appear below the horizon.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Therefore, Molniya orbit satellites have been launched, mainly in Russia, to alleviate this problem.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Molniya orbits can be an appealing alternative in such cases.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is highly inclined, guaranteeing good elevation over selected positions during the northern portion of the orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] (Elevation is the extent of the satellite's position above the horizon.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is designed so that the satellite spends the great majority of its time over the far northern latitudes, during which its ground footprint moves only slightly.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Its period is one half day, so that the satellite is available for operation over the targeted region for six to nine hours every second revolution.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In this way a constellation of three Molniya satellites (plus in-orbit spares) can provide uninterrupted coverage.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The first satellite of the Molniya series was launched on 23 April 1965 and was used for experimental transmission of TV signals from a Moscow uplink station to downlink stations located in Siberia and the Russian Far East, in Norilsk, Khabarovsk, Magadan and Vladivostok.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In November 1967 Soviet engineers created a unique system of national TV network of satellite television, called Orbita, that was based on Molniya satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In the United States, the National Polar-orbiting Operational Environmental Satellite System (NPOESS) was established in 1994 to consolidate the polar satellite operations of NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] NPOESS manages a number of satellites for various purposes; for example, METSAT for meteorological satellite, EUMETSAT for the European branch of the program, and METOP for meteorological operations.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] These orbits are Sun synchronous, meaning that they cross the equator at the same local time each day.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] For example, the satellites in the NPOESS (civilian) orbit will cross the equator, going from south to north, at times 1:30 P.M., 5:30 P.M., and 9:30 P.M.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] There are plans and initiatives to bring dedicated communications satellite beyond geostationary orbits.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] NASA proposed LunaNet as a data network aiming to provide a "Lunar Internet" for cis-lunar spacecraft and Installations.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Moonlight Initiative is an equivalent ESA project that is stated to be compatible and providing navigational services for the lunar surface.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Both programmes are satellite constellations of several satellites in various orbits around the Moon.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Other orbits are also planned to be used.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Positions in the Earth-Moon-Libration points are also proposed for communication satellites covering the Moon alike communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit cover the Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Also, dedicated communication satellites in orbits around Mars supporting different missions on surface and other orbits are considered, such as the Mars Telecommunications Orbiter.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The bandwidth available from a satellite depends upon the number of transponders provided by the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Each service (TV, Voice, Internet, radio) requires a different amount of bandwidth for transmission.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This is typically known as link budgeting and a network simulator can be used to arrive at the exact value.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Allocating frequencies to satellite services is a complicated process which requires international coordination and planning.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This is carried out under the auspices of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Within these regions, frequency bands are allocated to various satellite services, although a given service may be allocated different frequency bands in different regions.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The first and historically most important application for communication satellites was in intercontinental long distance telephony.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The fixed Public Switched Telephone Network relays telephone calls from land line telephones to an Earth station, where they are then transmitted to a geostationary satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Improvements in submarine communications cables through the use of fiber-optics caused some decline in the use of satellites for fixed telephony in the late 20th century.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite communications are still used in many applications today.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Remote islands such as Ascension Island, Saint Helena, Diego Garcia, and Easter Island, where no submarine cables are in service, need satellite telephones.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] There are also regions of some continents and countries where landline telecommunications are rare to non existent, for example large regions of South America, Africa, Canada, China, Russia, and Australia.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite communications also provide connection to the edges of Antarctica and Greenland.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Other land use for satellite phones are rigs at sea, a backup for hospitals, military, and recreation.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Ships at sea, as well as planes, often use satellite phones.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite phone systems can be accomplished by a number of means.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] On a large scale, often there will be a local telephone system in an isolated area with a link to the telephone system in a main land area.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] There are also services that will patch a radio signal to a telephone system.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] In this example, almost any type of satellite can be used.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite phones connect directly to a constellation of either geostationary or low-Earth-orbit satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Calls are then forwarded to a satellite teleport connected to the Public Switched Telephone Network .
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] As television became the main market, its demand for simultaneous delivery of relatively few signals of large bandwidth to many receivers being a more precise match for the capabilities of geosynchronous comsats.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Two satellite types are used for North American television and radio: Direct broadcast satellite (DBS), and Fixed Service Satellite (FSS).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The definitions of FSS and DBS satellites outside of North America, especially in Europe, are a bit more ambiguous.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Most satellites used for direct-to-home television in Europe have the same high power output as DBS-class satellites in North America, but use the same linear polarization as FSS-class satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Examples of these are the Astra, Eutelsat, and Hotbird spacecraft in orbit over the European continent.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Because of this, the terms FSS and DBS are more so used throughout the North American continent, and are uncommon in Europe.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Fixed Service Satellites use the C band, and the lower portions of the Ku band.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] FSS satellites are also used to distribute national cable channels to cable television headends.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Free-to-air satellite TV channels are also usually distributed on FSS satellites in the Ku band.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The Intelsat Americas 5, Galaxy 10R and AMC 3 satellites over North America provide a quite large amount of FTA channels on their Ku band transponders.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A direct broadcast satellite is a communications satellite that transmits to small DBS satellite dishes (usually 18 to 24 inches or 45 to 60 cm in diameter).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Direct broadcast satellites generally operate in the upper portion of the microwave Ku band.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] DBS technology is used for DTH-oriented (Direct-To-Home) satellite TV services, such as DirecTV, DISH Network and Orby TV in the United States, Bell Satellite TV and Shaw Direct in Canada, Freesat and Sky in the UK, Ireland, and New Zealand and DSTV in South Africa.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Operating at lower frequency and lower power than DBS, FSS satellites require a much larger dish for reception (3 to 8 feet (1 to 2.5 m) in diameter for Ku band, and 12 feet (3.6 m) or larger for C band).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] They use linear polarization for each of the transponders' RF input and output (as opposed to circular polarization used by DBS satellites), but this is a minor technical difference that users do not notice.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] FSS satellite technology was also originally used for DTH satellite TV from the late 1970s to the early 1990s in the United States in the form of TVRO (Television Receive Only) receivers and dishes.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It was also used in its Ku band form for the now-defunct Primestar satellite TV service.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Some satellites have been launched that have transponders in the Ka band, such as DirecTV's SPACEWAY-1 satellite, and Anik F2.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] NASA and ISRO have also launched experimental satellites carrying Ka band beacons recently.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Some manufacturers have also introduced special antennas for mobile reception of DBS television.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Using Global Positioning System (GPS) technology as a reference, these antennas automatically re-aim to the satellite no matter where or how the vehicle (on which the antenna is mounted) is situated.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] These mobile satellite antennas are popular with some recreational vehicle owners.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Such mobile DBS antennas are also used by JetBlue Airways for DirecTV (supplied by LiveTV, a subsidiary of JetBlue), which passengers can view on-board on LCD screens mounted in the seats.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Satellite radio offers audio broadcast services in some countries, notably the United States.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Mobile services allow listeners to roam a continent, listening to the same audio programming anywhere.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] A satellite radio or subscription radio (SR) is a digital radio signal that is broadcast by a communications satellite, which covers a much wider geographical range than terrestrial radio signals.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Amateur radio operators have access to amateur satellites, which have been designed specifically to carry amateur radio traffic.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Most such satellites operate as spaceborne repeaters, and are generally accessed by amateurs equipped with UHF or VHF radio equipment and highly directional antennas such as Yagis or dish antennas.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Due to launch costs, most current amateur satellites are launched into fairly low Earth orbits, and are designed to deal with only a limited number of brief contacts at any given time.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Some satellites also provide data-forwarding services using the X.25 or similar protocols.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] After the 1990s, satellite communication technology has been used as a means to connect to the Internet via broadband data connections.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] This can be very useful for users who are located in remote areas, and cannot access a broadband connection, or require high availability of services.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for military communications applications, such as Global Command and Control Systems.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Examples of military systems that use communication satellites are the MILSTAR, the DSCS, and the FLTSATCOM of the United States, NATO satellites, United Kingdom satellites (for instance Skynet), and satellites of the former Soviet Union.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] India has launched its first Military Communication satellite GSAT-7, its transponders operate in UHF, F, C and Ku band bands.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Typically military satellites operate in the UHF, SHF (also known as X-band) or EHF (also known as Ka band) frequency bands.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] Near-ground *in situ* environmental monitoring equipment (such as tide gauges, weather stations, weather buoys, and radiosondes), may use satellites for one-way data transmission or two-way telemetry and telecontrol.
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] It may be based on a secondary payload of a weather satellite (as in the case of GOES and METEOSAT and others in the Argos system) or in dedicated satellites (such as SCD).
[src:satellite-networking/communications-satellite] The data rate is typically much lower than in satellite Internet access.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] A **low Earth orbit** (**LEO**) is an orbit around Earth with a period of 128 minutes or less (making at least 11.25 orbits per day) and an eccentricity less than 0.25.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The term *LEO region* is used for the area of space below an altitude of 2,000 km (1,200 mi) (about one-third of Earth's radius).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Objects in orbits that pass through this zone, even if they have an apogee further out or are sub-orbital, are carefully tracked since they present a collision risk to the many LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The only human spaceflights to go beyond LEO are the lunar missions of the Apollo program from 1968 to 1972 and the Artemis II lunar flyby in 2026.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] All space stations as of 2026 have operated in geocentric orbits within LEO.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] A wide variety of sources define LEO in terms of altitude.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The altitude of an object in an elliptic orbit can vary significantly along the orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Even for circular orbits, the altitude above ground can vary by as much as 30 km (19 mi) (especially for polar orbits) due to the oblateness of Earth's spheroid figure and local topography.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] While definitions based on altitude are inherently ambiguous, most of them fall within the range specified by an orbit period of 128 minutes because, according to Kepler's third law, this corresponds to a semi-major axis of 8,413 km (5,228 mi).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] For circular orbits, this in turn corresponds to an altitude of 2,042 km (1,269 mi) above the mean radius of Earth, which is consistent with some of the upper altitude limits in some LEO definitions.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The LEO region is defined by some sources as a region in space that LEO orbits occupy.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some highly elliptical orbits may pass through the LEO region near their lowest altitude (or perigee) but are not in a LEO orbit because their highest altitude (or apogee) exceeds 2,000 km (1,243 mi).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Sub-orbital objects can also reach the LEO region but are not in a LEO orbit because they re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The distinction between LEO orbits and the LEO region is especially important for analysis of possible collisions between objects which may not themselves be in LEO but could collide with satellites or debris in LEO orbits.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The mean orbital velocity needed to maintain a stable low Earth orbit is about 7.8 km/s (4.8 mi/s), which translates to 28,000 km/h (17,000 mph).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] However, this depends on the exact altitude of the orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Calculated for a circular orbit of 200 km (120 mi) the orbital velocity is 7.79 km/s (4.84 mi/s), but for a higher 1,500 km (930 mi) orbit the velocity is reduced to 7.12 km/s (4.42 mi/s).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The launch vehicle's delta-v needed to achieve low Earth orbit starts around 9.4 km/s (5.8 mi/s).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The pull of gravity in LEO is only slightly less than on the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] This is because the distance to LEO from the Earth's surface is much less than the Earth's radius.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] However, an object in orbit is in a permanent free fall around Earth, because in orbit the gravitational force and the centrifugal force balance each other out.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] As a result, spacecraft in orbit continue to stay in orbit, and people inside or outside such craft continuously experience weightlessness.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Objects in LEO orbit Earth between the denser part of the atmosphere and below the inner Van Allen radiation belt.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] They encounter atmospheric drag from gases in the thermosphere (approximately 80–600 km above the surface) or exosphere (approximately 600 km or 400 mi and higher), depending on orbit height.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites in orbits involving altitudes below 300 km (190 mi) are subject to quick orbital decay due to atmospheric drag.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Equatorial low Earth orbits (**ELEO**) are a subset of LEO.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, with low orbital inclination, allow rapid revisit times over low-latitude locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Prograde equatorial LEOs also have lower delta-v launch requirements because they take advantage of the Earth's rotation.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Other useful LEO orbits, including polar orbits and Sun-synchronous orbits, have higher inclinations to the equator and provide coverage for higher latitudes on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some of the first generation of Starlink satellites used polar orbits which provide coverage everywhere on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Later Starlink constellations orbit at a lower inclination and provide more coverage for populated areas.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Higher orbits include medium Earth orbit (MEO), sometimes called intermediate circular orbit (ICO), and further above, geostationary orbit (GEO).
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Orbits higher than low orbit can lead to early failure of electronic components due to intense radiation and charge accumulation.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] In 2017, "very low Earth orbits" (**VLEO**) began to be seen in regulatory filings.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] These orbits, below about 450 km (280 mi), require the use of novel technologies for orbit raising because they operate in orbits that would ordinarily decay too soon to be economically useful.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] A low Earth orbit requires the lowest amount of energy for satellite placement.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] It provides high bandwidth and low communication latency.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites and space stations in LEO are more accessible for crew and servicing.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Since it requires less energy to place a satellite into a LEO, and a satellite there needs less powerful amplifiers for successful transmission, LEO is used for many communication applications, such as the Iridium phone system.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Some communication satellites use much higher geostationary orbits and move at the same angular velocity as the Earth as to appear stationary above one location on the planet.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Unlike geosynchronous satellites, satellites in low orbit have a small field of view and can only observe and communicate with a fraction of the Earth at a given time.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] This means that a large network (or constellation) of satellites is required to provide continuous coverage.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Satellites at lower altitudes of orbit are in the atmosphere and suffer from rapid orbital decay, requiring either periodic re-boosting to maintain stable orbits, or the launching of replacements for those that re-enter the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The effects of adding such quantities of vaporized metals to Earth's stratosphere are potentially of concern but currently unknown.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The LEO environment is becoming congested with space debris because of the frequency of object launches.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] This has caused growing concern in recent years, since collisions at orbital velocities can be dangerous or deadly.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] Collisions can produce additional space debris, creating a domino effect known as the Kessler syndrome.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] NASA's Orbital Debris Program tracks over 25,000 objects larger than 10 cm diameter in LEO, while the estimated number between 1 and 10 cm is 500,000, and the number of particles bigger than 1 mm exceeds 100 million.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The particles travel at speeds up to 7.8 km/s (28,000 km/h; 17,500 mph), so even a small impact can severely damage a spacecraft.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The lifespan of space debris can vary wildly depending on their respective ballistic coefficient, and most importantly their initial orbit altitude.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] At lower orbit altitudes such as 400 km small spacecraft can decay within 5 years.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] However at altitudes above 500 km some spacecraft will take more than 25 years to deorbit.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The oldest piece of space debris that can be found in LEO is the Vanguard 1 satellite and its third-stage booster.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] The satellite was launched in 1958 and currently has a perigee of 651 km and an apogee of 4,226 km, placing part of its orbit within the higher region of Low Earth Orbit and extending into medium Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/low-earth-orbit] It is currently expected to remain in orbit for 240 years.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:satellite-networking/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] A **satellite constellation** is a group of artificial satellites working together as a system.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Unlike a single satellite, a constellation can provide permanent global or near-global coverage, such that at any time everywhere on Earth at least one satellite is visible.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Satellites are typically placed in sets of complementary orbital planes and connect to globally distributed ground stations.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] They may also use inter-satellite communication.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Satellites in medium Earth orbit (MEO) and low Earth orbit (LEO) are often deployed in satellite constellations, because the coverage area provided by a single satellite only covers a small area that moves as the satellite travels at the high angular velocity needed to maintain its orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Many MEO or LEO satellites are needed to maintain continuous coverage over an area.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] This contrasts with geostationary satellites, where a single satellite, at a much higher altitude and moving at the same angular velocity as the rotation of the Earth's surface, provides permanent coverage over a large area.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] For some applications, in particular digital connectivity, the lower altitude of MEO and LEO satellite constellations provide advantages over a geostationary satellite, with lower path losses (reducing power requirements and costs) and latency.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] The propagation delay for a round-trip internet protocol transmission via a geostationary satellite can be over 600 ms, but as low as 125 ms for a MEO satellite or 30 ms for a LEO system.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Designing a satellite constellation (i.e., determining the orbital distribution of its constituents) is a complex problem that typically uses satellite-to-target coverage as the primary figure of merit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Naturally, the resulting constellation depends on the mission requirements and objectives and can be characterized by its geometry.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] That is, either symmetric or asymmetric constellations.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Symmetric constellations are traditionally proposed for applications that require global coverage (e.g., telecommunications).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Notable symmetric constellations proposed in the literature include Walker Delta and Star , and Rosette.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are typically adopted when regional coverage (i.e., the distribution of targets is concentrated around specific locations rather than being globally uniform) is required.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Asymmetric constellations are proposed to address disaster monitoring, orbital debris remediation, and cislunar space domain awareness.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] The need for optimization in constellation design arises from the large number of degrees of freedom in the design space.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] For example, the payload characteristics, required temporal coverage resolution (e.g., continuous or discontinuous), targets' distribution, and candidate orbits.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] There are a large number of constellations that may satisfy a particular mission.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Usually constellations are designed so that the satellites have similar orbits, eccentricity and inclination so that any perturbations affect each satellite in approximately the same way.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] In this way, the geometry can be preserved without excessive station-keeping thereby reducing the fuel usage and hence increasing the life of the satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Another consideration is that the phasing of each satellite in an orbital plane maintains sufficient separation to avoid collisions or interference at orbit plane intersections.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] A class of circular orbit geometries that has become popular is the Walker Delta Pattern constellation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] This has an associated notation to describe it which was proposed by John Walker.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] For example, the Galileo navigation system is a Walker Delta 56°: 24/3/1 constellation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] This means there are 24 satellites in 3 planes inclined at 56 degrees, spanning the 360 degrees around the equator.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] The "1" defines the phasing between the planes, and how they are spaced.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] The Walker Delta is also known as the Ballard rosette, after A.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Ballard's notation is (t,p,m) where m is a multiple of the fractional offset between planes.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Another popular constellation type is the near-polar Walker Star, which is used by Iridium.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Here, the satellites are in near-polar circular orbits across approximately 180 degrees, travelling north on one side of the Earth, and south on the other.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] The active satellites in the full Iridium constellation form a Walker Star of 86.4°: 66/6/2, i.e. the phasing repeats every two planes.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Walker uses similar notation for stars and deltas, which can be confusing.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] These sets of circular orbits at constant altitude are sometimes referred to as orbital shells.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] In spaceflight, an **orbital shell** is a set of artificial satellites in circular orbits at a certain fixed altitude.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] In the design of satellite constellations, an orbital shell usually refers to a collection of circular orbits with the same altitude and, oftentimes, orbital inclination, distributed evenly in celestial longitude (and mean anomaly).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] For a sufficiently high inclination and altitude the orbital shell covers the entire orbited body.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] In other cases the coverage extends up to a certain maximum latitude.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] Several existing satellite constellations typically use a single orbital shell.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-constellation] New large megaconstellations have been proposed that consist of multiple orbital shells.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Following the launch of the first satellite, Sputnik 1, by the Soviet Union in October 1957, the US successfully launched the Explorer 1 satellite in 1958.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The first commercial communications satellite was Telstar 1, built by Bell Labs and launched in July 1962.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The idea of a geosynchronous satellite—one that could orbit the Earth above the equator and remain fixed by following the Earth's rotation—was first proposed by Herman Potočnik in 1928 and popularised by the science fiction author Arthur C.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Clarke in a paper in *Wireless World* in 1945.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The first satellite to successfully reach geostationary orbit was Syncom3, built by Hughes Aircraft for NASA and launched on August 19, 1963.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Succeeding generations of communications satellites featuring larger capacities and improved performance characteristics were adopted for use in television delivery, military applications and telecommunications purposes.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Following the invention of the Internet and the World Wide Web, geostationary satellites attracted interest as a potential means of providing Internet access.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A significant enabler of satellite-delivered Internet has been the opening up of the Ka band for satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In December 1993, Hughes Aircraft Co. filed with the Federal Communications Commission for a license to launch the first Ka-band satellite, Spaceway.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 1995, the FCC issued a call for more Ka-band satellite applications, attracting applications from 15 companies.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Among those were EchoStar, Lockheed Martin, GE-Americom, Motorola and KaStar Satellite, which later became WildBlue, which then became Viasat.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Among prominent aspirants in the early-stage satellite Internet sector was Teledesic, an ambitious and ultimately failed project funded in part by Microsoft that ended up costing more than $9 billion.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Teledesic's idea was to create a satellite Internet constellation of hundreds of low-orbiting satellites in the Ka-band frequency, providing inexpensive Internet access with download speeds of up to 720 Mbit/s.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] However, the project was abandoned in 2003.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Teledesic's failure, coupled with the bankruptcy filings of the satellite communications providers Iridium Communications Inc. and Globalstar, dampened marketplace enthusiasm for satellite Internet development.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The first Internet-ready satellite for consumers was launched in September 2003.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 2004, with the launch of Anik F2, the first high-throughput satellite, a class of next-generation satellites providing improved capacity and bandwidth became operational.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] More recently, high throughput satellites such as ViaSat's ViaSat-1 satellite in 2011 and HughesNet's Jupiter in 2012 have achieved further improvements, elevating downstream data rates from 1 to 3 Mbit/s up to 12 to 15 Mbit/s and beyond.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Internet access services tied to these satellites are targeted largely to rural residents as an alternative to Internet service via dial-up, ADSL or classic FSSes.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 2013, the first four satellites of the O3b constellation were launched into medium Earth orbit (MEO) to provide internet access to the "other three billion" people without stable internet access at that time.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Over the next six years, 16 further satellites joined the constellation, now owned and operated by SES.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Since 2014, a rising number of companies announced working on internet access using satellite constellations in low Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] SpaceX, OneWeb and Amazon all planned to launch more than 1000 satellites each.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] OneWeb alone raised $1.7 billion by February 2017 for the project, and SpaceX raised over one billion in the first half of 2019 for their service called Starlink.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] They expected more than $30 billion in revenue by 2025 from its satellite constellation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Starlink, as of February 2024, has 5,402 operational satellites in orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Many planned constellations employ laser communication for inter-satellite links to effectively create a space-based internet backbone.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of 2017, airlines such as Delta and American have been introducing satellite internet as a means of combating limited bandwidth on airplanes and offering passengers usable internet speeds.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In September 2017, SES announced the next generation of O3b satellites and service, named O3b mPOWER, a constellation of seven MEO satellites to deliver 10 terabits of capacity globally through 30,000 spot beams for broadband internet services.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The number of O3b mPOWER satellites ordered was subsequently increased to 11 and then 13, and on 16 December 2022, the first two O3b mPOWER satellites were successfully launched, with four more in 2023, and the service began operations alongside the existing O3b constellation in April 2024.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Consumers experienced performance increases in the 2020s, largely based on the decision of services like Starlink to deploy satellites at the low earth orbit level, which allowed for much lower latency than internet satellites deployed at the geostationary level, as they traditionally were.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of 2024, companies providing home internet service in the United States via satellite included ViaSat, through its Exede brand, EchoStar, through subsidiary HughesNet, Starlink, and Amazon Leo.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The EU plans to commence the IRIS² project in the 2020s.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of 2023, China is in the process of developing its own, state-owned, satellite internet constellation, run by Chinasat.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of 2023, India’s main offerings in the space were Oneweb and JioSpaceFiber, with the country considering licenses for Starlink and Project Kuiper.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Other components of a satellite Internet system include a modem at the user end which links the user's network with the transceiver, and a centralized network operations centre (NOC) for monitoring the entire system.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Working in concert with a broadband gateway, the satellite operates a Star network topology where all network communication passes through the network's hub processor, which is at the centre of the star.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] With this configuration, the number of ground stations that can be connected to the hub is virtually limitless.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Marketed as the centre of the new broadband satellite networks are a new generation of high-powered GEO satellites positioned 35,786 kilometres (22,236 mi) above the equator, operating in Ka-band (18.3–30 GHz) mode.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] These new purpose-built satellites are designed and optimized for broadband applications, employing many narrow spot beams, which target a much smaller area than the broad beams used by earlier communication satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This spot beam technology allows satellites to reuse assigned bandwidth multiple times which can enable them to achieve much higher overall capacity than conventional broad beam satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The spot beams can also increase performance and consequential capacity by focusing more power and increased receiver sensitivity into defined concentrated areas.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Spot beams are designated as one of two types: subscriber spot beams, which transmit to and from the subscriber-side terminal, and gateway spot beams, which transmit to/from a service provider ground station.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Note that moving off the tight footprint of a spotbeam can degrade performance significantly.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Also, spotbeams can make the use of other significant new technologies impossible, including 'Carrier in Carrier' modulation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In conjunction with the satellite's spot-beam technology, a bent-pipe architecture has traditionally been employed in the network in which the satellite functions as a bridge in space, connecting two communication points on the ground.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The term "bent-pipe" is used to describe the shape of the data path between sending and receiving antennas, with the satellite positioned at the point of the bend.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Simply put, the satellite's role in this network arrangement is to relay signals from the end user's terminal to the ISP's gateways, and back again without processing the signal at the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite receives, amplifies, and redirects a carrier on a specific radio frequency through a signal path called a transponder.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Some satellite constellations in LEO such as Starlink and the proposed Telesat constellation will employ laser communication equipment for high-throughput optical inter-satellite links.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The interconnected satellites allow for direct routing of user data from satellite to satellite and effectively create a space-based optical mesh network that will enable seamless network management and continuity of service.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite has its own set of antennas to receive communication signals from Earth and to transmit signals to their target location.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] These antennas and transponders are part of the satellite's "payload", which is designed to receive and transmit signals to and from various places on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] What enables this transmission and reception in the payload transponders is a repeater subsystem (RF (radio frequency) equipment) used to change frequencies, filter, separate, amplify and group signals before routing them to their destination address on Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite's high-gain receiving antenna passes the transmitted data to the transponder which filters, translates and amplifies them, then redirects them to the transmitting antenna on board.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The signal is then routed to a specific ground location through a channel known as a carrier.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Along with dramatic advances in satellite technology over the past decade, ground equipment has similarly evolved, benefiting from higher levels of integration and increasing processing power, expanding both capacity and performance boundaries.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The gateway—or gateway Earth station—is also referred to as a ground station, teleport or hub.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The term is sometimes used to describe just the antenna dish portion, or it can refer to the complete system with all associated components.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In short, the gateway receives radio wave signals from the satellite on the last leg of the return or upstream payload, carrying the request originating from the end-user's site.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite modem at the gateway location demodulates the incoming signal from the outdoor antenna into IP packets and sends the packets to the local network.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Access server/gateways manage traffic transported to/from the Internet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Once the initial request has been processed by the gateway's servers, sent to and returned from the Internet, the requested information is sent back as a forward or downstream payload to the end-user via the satellite, which directs the signal to the subscriber terminal.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Each Gateway provides the connection to the Internet backbone for the gateway beam(s) it serves.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The system of gateways comprising the satellite ground system provides all network services for satellite and corresponding terrestrial connectivity.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Each gateway provides a multiservice access network for subscriber terminal connections to the Internet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As the continental United States is north of the equator, all gateway and subscriber dish antenna must have an unobstructed view of the southern sky.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Because of the satellite's geostationary orbit, the gateway antenna can stay pointed at a fixed position.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For the customer-provided equipment (i.e.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] At the far end of the outdoor unit is typically a small (2–3-foot, 60 to 90 cm diameter), reflective dish-type radio antenna.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The VSAT antenna must also have an unobstructed view of the sky to allow for proper line-of-sight (L-O-S) to the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] There are four physical characteristic settings used to ensure that the antenna is configured correctly at the satellite, which are: azimuth, elevation, polarization, and skew.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The combination of these settings gives the outdoor unit a L-O-S to the chosen satellite and makes data transmission possible.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] These parameters are generally set at the time the equipment is installed, along with a beam assignment (Ka-band only); these steps must all be taken prior to the actual activation of service.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Transmit and receive components are typically mounted at the focal point of the antenna which receives/sends data from/to the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite modem serves as an interface between the outdoor unit and customer-provided equipment (i.e.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] PC, router) and controls satellite transmission and reception.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] From the sending device (computer, router, etc.) it receives an input bitstream and converts or modulates it into radio waves, reversing that order for incoming transmissions, which is called demodulation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Consumer grade satellite modems typically employ either the DOCSIS or WiMAX telecommunication standard to communicate with the assigned gateway.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Latency (commonly referred to as "ping time") is the delay between requesting data and the receipt of a response, or in the case of one-way communication, between the actual moment of a signal's broadcast and the time it is received at its destination.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A radio signal takes about 120 milliseconds to reach a geostationary satellite and then 120 milliseconds to reach the ground station, so nearly 1/4 of a second overall.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Typically, during perfect conditions, the physics involved in satellite communications account for approximately 550 milliseconds of latency round-trip time.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The longer latency is the primary difference between a standard terrestrial-based network and a geostationary satellite-based network.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The round-trip latency of a geostationary satellite communications network can be more than 12 times that of a terrestrial based network.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The effects of this delay may be mitigated using data compression, TCP-acceleration, and HTTP pre-fetching.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A geostationary orbit (or geostationary Earth orbit/GEO) is a geosynchronous orbit directly above the Earth's equator (0° latitude), with a period equal to the Earth's rotational period and an orbital eccentricity of approximately zero (i.e. a "circular orbit").
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] An object in a geostationary orbit appears motionless, at a fixed position in the sky, to ground observers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Launchers often place communications satellites and weather satellites in geostationary orbits, so that the satellite antennas that communicate with them do not have to move to track them, but can point permanently at the position in the sky where the satellites stay.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Due to the constant 0° latitude and circularity of geostationary orbits, satellites in GEO differ in location by longitude only.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Compared to ground-based communication, all geostationary satellite communications experience higher latency due to the signal having to travel 35,786 km (22,236 mi) to a satellite in geostationary orbit and back to Earth again.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Even at the speed of light (about 300,000 km/s or 186,000 miles per second), this delay can appear significant.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] If all other signaling delays could be eliminated, it still takes a radio signal about 250 milliseconds (ms), or about a quarter of a second, to travel to the satellite and back to the ground.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The absolute minimum total amount of delay varies, due to the satellite staying in one place in the sky, while ground-based users can be directly below (with a roundtrip latency of 239.6 ms), or far to the side of the planet near the horizon (with a roundtrip latency of 279.0 ms).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For an Internet packet, that delay is doubled before a reply is received.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Factoring in other normal delays from network sources gives a typical one-way connection latency of 500 to 700 ms from the user to the ISP, or about 1,000 to 1,400 ms latency for the total round-trip time (RTT) back to the user.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This is more than most dial-up users experience at typically 150–200 ms total latency, and much higher than the typical 15 to 40 ms latency experienced by users of other high-speed Internet services, such as cable or VDSL..
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Certain acceleration features are often present in recent technology developments embedded in satellite Internet equipment.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Latency also impacts the initiation of secure Internet connections such as SSL which require the exchange of numerous pieces of data between web server and web client.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Although these pieces of data are small, the multiple round trips involved in the handshake produce long delays compared to other forms of Internet connectivity, as documented by Stephen T.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Cobb in a 2011 report published by the Rural Mobile and Broadband Alliance.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This annoyance extends to entering and editing data using some Software as a Service or SaaS applications as well as in other forms of online work.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Functions, like live interactive access to a distant computer—such as virtual private networks, can be affected by the high latency.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Many TCP protocols were not designed to work in high-latency environments.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Medium Earth orbit (MEO) and low Earth orbit (LEO) satellite constellations do not have such long delays, as the satellites are closer to the ground.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] MEO satellites require higher power transmissions than LEO to achieve the same signal strength at the ground station but their higher altitude also provides less orbital overcrowding, and their slower orbit speed reduces both Doppler shift and the size and complexity of the constellation required.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A proposed alternative to relay satellites is a special-purpose high altitude platform stations aircraft, which would fly along a circular path above a fixed ground location, operating under autonomous computer control at a height of approximately 20,000 meters.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This project was cancelled in 2012 before it became operational.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Onboard batteries would charge during daylight hours through solar panels covering the wings and would provide power to the plane during night.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Ground-based satellite internet dishes would relay signals to and from the aircraft, resulting in a greatly reduced round-trip signal latency of only 0.25 milliseconds.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The planes could potentially run for long periods without refueling.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Several such schemes involving various types of aircraft have been proposed in the past.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Satellite communications are affected by moisture and various forms of precipitation (such as rain or snow) in the signal path between end users or ground stations and the satellite being utilized.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This interference with the signal is known as *rain fade*.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The effects are less pronounced on the lower frequency 'L' and 'C' bands but can become quite severe on the higher frequency 'Ku' and 'Ka' band.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For satellite Internet services in tropical areas with heavy rain, use of the C band (4/6 GHz) with a circular polarisation satellite is popular.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Satellite communications on the Ka band (19/29 GHz) can use special techniques such as large *rain margins*, *adaptive uplink power control* and *reduced bit rates* during precipitation.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The amount of time during which service is lost can be reduced by increasing the size of the satellite communication dish so as to gather more of the satellite signal on the downlink and also to provide a stronger signal on the uplink.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Modern consumer-grade dish antennas tend to be fairly small, which reduces the rain margin or increases the required satellite downlink power and cost.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] However, it is often more economical to build a more expensive satellite and smaller, less expensive consumer antennas than to increase the consumer antenna size to reduce the satellite cost.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Large commercial dishes of 3.7 m to 13 m diameter can be used to achieve increased rain margins and also to reduce the cost per bit by allowing for more efficient modulation codes.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Alternately, larger aperture antennae can require less power from the satellite to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Satellites typically use photovoltaic solar power, so there is no expense for the energy itself, but a more powerful satellite will require larger, more powerful solar panels and electronics, often including a larger transmitting antenna.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The larger satellite components not only increase materials costs but also increase the weight of the satellite, and in general, the cost to launch a satellite into an orbit is directly proportional to its weight.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Modulated carriers can be dynamically altered in response to rain problems or other link impairments using a process called adaptive coding and modulation, or "ACM".
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] ACM allows the bit rates to be increased substantially during normal clear sky conditions, increasing the number of bits per Hz transmitted, and thus reducing overall cost per bit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Adaptive coding requires some sort of a return or feedback channel which can be via any available means, satellite or terrestrial.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Two objects are said to be within line of sight if a straight line between the objects can be connected without any interference, such as a mountain.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] An object beyond the horizon is below the line of sight and, therefore, can be difficult to communicate with.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Typically a completely clear line of sight between the dish and the satellite is required for the system to work optimally.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In addition to the signal being susceptible to absorption and scattering by moisture, the signal is similarly impacted by the presence of trees and other vegetation in the path of the signal.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As the radio frequency decreases, to below 900 MHz, penetration through vegetation increases, but most satellite communications operate above 2 GHz making them sensitive to even minor obstructions such as tree foliage.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A dish installation in the winter must factor in plant foliage growth that will appear in the spring and summer.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Even if there is a direct line of sight between the transmitting and receiving antenna, reflections from objects near the path of the signal can decrease apparent signal power through phase cancellations.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Whether and how much signal is lost from a reflection is determined by the location of the object in the Fresnel zone of the antennas.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Home or consumer grade two-way satellite Internet service involves both sending and receiving data from a remote very-small-aperture terminal (VSAT) via satellite to a hub telecommunications port (teleport), which then relays data via the terrestrial Internet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite dish at each location must be precisely pointed to avoid interference with other satellites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] At each VSAT site the uplink frequency, bit rate and power must be accurately set, under control of the service provider hub.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] There are several types of two-way satellite Internet services, including time-division multiple access (TDMA) and single channel per carrier (SCPC).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Two-way systems can be simple VSAT terminals with a 60–100 cm dish and output power of only a few watts intended for consumers and small business or larger systems that provide more bandwidth.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Such systems are frequently marketed as "satellite broadband" and can cost two to three times as much per month as land-based systems such as ADSL.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The modems required for this service are often proprietary, but some are compatible with several different providers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] They are also expensive, costing in the range of US$600 to $2000.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The two-way "iLNB" used on the SES Broadband terminal dish has a transmitter and single-polarity receive LNB, both operating in the Ku band.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Pricing for SES Broadband modems range from €299 to €350.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] These types of system are generally unsuitable for use on moving vehicles, although some dishes may be fitted to an automatic pan and tilt mechanism to continuously re-align the dish—but these are more expensive.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The technology for SES Broadband was delivered by a Belgian company called Newtec.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Consumer satellite Internet customers range from individual home users with one PC to large remote business sites with several hundred PCs.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Home users tend to use shared satellite capacity to reduce the cost, while still allowing high peak bit rates when congestion is absent.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] There are usually restrictive time-based bandwidth allowances so that each user gets their fair share, according to their payment.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] When a user exceeds their allowance, the company may slow down their access, deprioritise their traffic or charge for the excess bandwidth used.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For consumer satellite Internet, the allowance can typically range from 200 MB per day to 25 GB per month.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A shared download carrier may have a bit rate of 1 to 40 Mbit/s and be shared by up to 100 to 4,000 end users.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The uplink direction for shared user customers is normally time-division multiple access (TDMA), which involves transmitting occasional short packet bursts in between other users (similar to how a cellular phone shares a cell tower).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Each remote location may also be equipped with a telephone modem; the connections for this are as with a conventional dial-up ISP.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Two-way satellite systems may sometimes use the modem channel in both directions for data where latency is more important than bandwidth, reserving the satellite channel for download data where bandwidth is more important than latency, such as for file transfers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 2006, the European Commission sponsored the UNIC Project which aimed to develop an end-to-end scientific test bed for the distribution of new broadband interactive TV-centric services delivered over low-cost two-way satellite to actual end-users in the home.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The UNIC architecture employs DVB-S2 standard for downlink and DVB-RCS standard for uplink.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Normal VSAT dishes (1.2 to 2.4 m diameter) are widely used for VoIP phone services.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] A voice call is sent by means of packets via the satellite and Internet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Using coding and compression techniques the bit rate needed per call is only 10.8 kbit/s each way.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] These usually come in the shape of a self-contained flat rectangular box that needs to be pointed in the general direction of the satellite—unlike VSAT the alignment need not be very precise and the modems have built in signal strength meters to help the user align the device properly.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The modems have commonly used connectors such as Ethernet or Universal Serial Bus (USB).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Some also have an integrated Bluetooth transceiver and double as a satellite phone.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The modems also tend to have their own batteries so they can be connected to a laptop without draining its battery.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The most common such system is INMARSAT's BGAN—these terminals are about the size of a briefcase and have near-symmetric connection speeds of around 350 to 500 kbit/s.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Smaller modems exist like those offered by Thuraya but only connect at 444 kbit/s in a limited coverage area.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] At $5 to $7 per megabyte on average, portable satellite internet is typically more expensive than other modes of Internet access, with modems usually costing between $1,000 and $5,000.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Due to this, it is most often used on vehicles without access to other modes of Internet access, such as seafaring vessels.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For many years satellite phones have been able to connect to the Internet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Bandwidth varies from about 2400 bit/s for Iridium network satellites and ACeS based phones to 15 kbit/s upstream and 60 kbit/s downstream for Thuraya handsets.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Globalstar also provides Internet access at 9.6 kbit/s; like Iridium and ACeS a dial-up connection is required and is billed per minute, however both Globalstar and Iridium are planning to launch new satellites offering always-on data services at higher rates.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] With Thuraya phones the 9.6 kbit/s dial-up connection is also possible, the 60 kbit/s service is always-on and the user is billed for data transferred (about $5 per megabyte).
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The phones can be connected to a laptop or other computer using a USB or RS-232 interface.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Due to the low bandwidths involved it is extremely slow to browse the web with such a connection, but useful for sending email, Secure Shell data and using other low-bandwidth protocols.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Since satellite phones tend to have omnidirectional antennas no alignment is required as long as there is a line of sight between the phone and the satellite.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] One-way terrestrial return satellite Internet systems are used with conventional dial-up Internet access, with outbound (upstream) data traveling through a telephone modem, but downstream data sent via satellite at a higher rate.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In the U.S., an FCC license is required for the uplink station only; no license is required for the users.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Another type of one-way satellite Internet system uses General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) for the back-channel.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Using standard GPRS or Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE), costs are reduced for higher effective rates if the upload volume is very low, and also because this service is not per-time charged, but charged by volume uploaded.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] GPRS as return improves mobility when the service is provided by a satellite that transmits in the field of 100 to 200 kW.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Using a 33 cm wide satellite dish, a notebook and a normal GPRS equipped GSM phone, users can get mobile satellite broadband.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The transmitting station has two components, consisting of a high-speed Internet connection to serve many customers at once, and the satellite uplink to broadcast requested data to the customers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The ISP's routers connect to proxy servers which can enforce quality of service (QoS) bandwidth limits and guarantees for each customer's traffic.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Often, nonstandard IP stacks are used to address the latency and asymmetry problems of the satellite connection.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As with one-way receive systems, data sent over the satellite link is generally also encrypted, as otherwise it would be accessible to anyone with a satellite receiver.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Many IP-over-satellite implementations use paired proxy servers at both endpoints so that certain communications between clients and servers need not to accept the latency inherent in a satellite connection.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] For similar reasons, there exist special Virtual private network (VPN) implementations designed for use over satellite links because standard VPN software cannot handle the long packet travel times.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Upload speeds are limited by the user's dial-up modem, while download speeds can be very fast compared to dial-up, using the modem only as the control channel for packet acknowledgement.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Latency is still high, although lower than full two-way geostationary satellite Internet, since only half of the data path is via satellite, the other half being via the terrestrial channel.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] One-way broadcast satellite Internet systems are used for Internet Protocol (IP) broadcast-based data, audio and video distribution.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In the United States, a Federal Communications Commission (FCC) license is required only for the uplink station, not for its users.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Note that most Internet protocols will not work correctly over one-way access, since they require a return channel.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] However, Internet content such as web pages can still be distributed over a one-way system by "pushing" them out to local storage at end user sites, though full interactivity is not possible.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This is much like TV or radio content which offers little user interface.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The broadcast mechanism may include compression and error correction to help ensure the one-way broadcast is properly received.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The data may also be rebroadcast periodically, so that receivers that did not previously succeed will have additional chances to try downloading again.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The data may also be encrypted so that while anyone can receive the data, only certain destinations are able to actually decode and use the broadcast data.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Authorized users only need to have possession of either a short decryption key or an automatic rolling code device that uses its own highly accurate independent timing mechanism to decrypt the data.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Similar to one-way terrestrial return, satellite Internet access may include interfaces to the public switched telephone network for squawk box applications.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] An Internet connection is not required, but many applications include a File Transfer Protocol (FTP) server to queue data for broadcast.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Most one-way broadcast applications require custom programming at the remote sites.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The software at the remote site must filter, store, present a selection interface to and display the data.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The software at the transmitting station must provide access control, priority queuing, sending, and encapsulating of the data.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In its report released in February, 2013, the Federal Communications Commission noted significant advances in satellite Internet performance.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The FCC's Measuring Broadband America report also ranked the major ISPs by how close they came to delivering on advertised speeds.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In this category, satellite Internet topped the list, with 90% of subscribers seeing speeds at 140% or better than what was advertised.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Much of the slowdown associated with satellite Internet is that for each request, many roundtrips must be completed before any useful data can be received by the requester.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Special IP stacks and proxies can also reduce latency through lessening the number of roundtrips, or simplifying and reducing the length of protocol headers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Optimization technologies include TCP acceleration, HTTP pre-fetching and DNS caching among many others.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] See the Space Communications Protocol Specifications standard (SCPS), developed by NASA and adopted widely by commercial and military equipment and software providers in the market space.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The WINDS satellite was launched on February 23, 2008.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The WINDS satellite is used to provide broadband Internet services to Japan and locations across the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The satellite to provides a maximum speed of 155 Mbit/s down and 6 Mbit/s up to residences with a 45 cm aperture antenna and a 1.2 Gbit/s connection to businesses with a 5-meter antenna.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] It has reached the end of its design life expectancy.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] SkyTerra-1 was launched in mid-November 2010, providing North America, while Hylas-1 was launched in November 2010, targeting Europe.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] On December 26, 2010, Eutelsat's KA-SAT was launched.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] It covers the European continent with 80 spot beams—focused signals that cover an area a few hundred kilometers across Europe and the Mediterranean.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Spot beams allow for frequencies to be effectively reused in multiple regions without interference.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Each of the spot beams has an overall capacity of 900 Mbit/s and the entire satellite will has a capacity of 70 Gbit/s.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] 19, 2011 from Baikonur, Kazakhstan, offering 140 Gbit/s of total throughput capacity, through the Exede Internet service.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Passengers aboard JetBlue Airways can use this service since 2015.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The service has also been expanded to United Airlines, American Airlines, Scandinavian Airlines, Virgin America and Qantas.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] The EchoStar XVII satellite was launched July 5, 2012 by Arianespace and was placed in its permanent geosynchronous orbital slot of 107.1° West longitude, servicing HughesNet.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] This Ka-band satellite has over 100 Gbit/s of throughput capacity.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 2015 and 2016, the Australian Government launched two Sky Muster geostationary satellites to provide internet to regional Australians and residents of External Territories, such as Norfolk Island and Christmas Island.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] In 2006 and 2015, the Argentinian company ARSAT launched the ARSAT-1 and ARSAT-2 satellites, respectively.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Providing internet and TV access to remote locations in its country of origin.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Since 2013, the O3b satellite constellation (in Medium Earth Orbit at an altitude of 8,063 km) claims an end-to-end round-trip latency of 140 ms for data services.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of September 2024, 6,426 Starlink satellites are orbiting Earth.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] As of September 2024, Starlink has over 4 million subscribers.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] There are 648 Oneweb has satellites in low Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-networking/satellite-internet-access] Satellite communications are used for data transmission, remote instrument diagnostics, for physical satellite and oceanographic measurements from the sea surface (e.g. sea surface temperature and sea surface height) to the ocean floor, and for seismological analyses.
